The correct answer is&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt; Prokaryotic cells.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Prokaryotic cells&lt;/strong&gt; are the cells that&lt;strong&gt; lack&lt;/strong&gt; a &lt;strong&gt;well-defined nucleus &lt;/strong&gt;and other &lt;strong&gt;membrane-bound organelles.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These cells have a &lt;strong&gt;single, circular chromosome &lt;/strong&gt;that floats freely in the&lt;strong&gt; cytoplasm.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Prokaryotic cells are usually &lt;strong&gt;smaller in size&lt;/strong&gt; than &lt;strong&gt;eukaryotic cells&lt;/strong&gt; and are found in &lt;strong&gt;bacteria and archaea.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&lt;strong&gt; absence of a nuclear membrane&lt;/strong&gt; in prokaryotic cells enables them to &lt;strong&gt;replicate faster &lt;/strong&gt;than eukaryotic cells.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cheek cells&lt;/strong&gt; are eukaryotic cells that contain a &lt;strong&gt;well-defined nucleus&lt;/strong&gt; and other &lt;strong&gt;membrane-bound organelles.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;These cells are obtained from the &lt;strong&gt;inner lining of the cheek&lt;/strong&gt; and are commonly used for &lt;strong&gt;DNA analysis.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Eukaryotic cells&lt;/strong&gt; are cells that contain a&lt;strong&gt; well-defined nucleus &lt;/strong&gt;and other membrane-bound organelles.&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;These cells are found in&lt;strong&gt; plants, animals, fungi, and protists.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Onion cells &lt;/strong&gt;are &lt;strong&gt;eukaryotic&lt;/strong&gt; cells that are commonly used in &lt;strong&gt;biology labs&lt;/strong&gt; for studying &lt;strong&gt;cell division&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;cell structure&lt;/strong&gt;. &lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;These cells contain a &lt;strong&gt;well-defined nucleus&lt;/strong&gt; and other &lt;strong&gt;membrane-bound organelles&lt;/strong&gt;. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Hence, the statement &amp;quot;The cells having nuclear material without nuclear membrane are termed as &lt;strong&gt;Prokaryotic cells&amp;quot; is correct.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Silver&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color:  (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Conductivity:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;The measure of the&amp;nbsp;ease at which an electric charge&amp;nbsp;can pass through a material is called electrical conductivity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Conductor&lt;/span&gt;: The material which has high conductivity is called the conductor.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Non-conductor:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The material which has very low conductivity is called non-conductor.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Metal has high conductivity&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and non-metal has very low conductivity&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Electrical Conductivity&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the evaluation of a material&amp;#39;s ability to allow the transport of an electric charge.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Silver is by far the most electrically conductive metal on earth&lt;/span&gt;. Since silver has only one valence electron which is free to move around with little resistance, it has great electrical and thermal conductivity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;After silver,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;copper is the second most electrically conductive metal.&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;Gold and Aluminium are other metals which are good conductors of electricity.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;width:350px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;thead&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;th&gt;Material&lt;/th&gt;
			&lt;th&gt;Description&lt;/th&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/thead&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Glass&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Glass is a non-crystalline amorphous solid that often appears and has widespread practical, technological, and decorative applications. Its uses include window panes, drinkware, and optoelectronics. Its most significant characteristics include transparency, brittleness, hardness, and resistance to chemical attack.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Mica&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Mica is a group of silicate minerals that are widely distributed in different types of rock. Mica has a crystalline structure that allows it to be split into thin sheets. These sheets are flexible, heat-resistant, and electrically insulating, making mica useful in the electronics and electrical industries, and in the manufacturing of cosmetics.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Ebonite&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Ebonite is a type of hard rubber, also known as vulcanite or hard vulcanized rubber. It&amp;#39;s made by treating rubber with sulfur at high temperatures, a process known as vulcanization. The resulting material is hard and black, resembling ebony, which gives it its name. Ebonite has high electrical resistance and chemical stability, making it appropriate for applications like electrical insulators and bowling balls. It is also historically used for wind musical instruments like clarinets and mouthpieces of other wind instruments because of its excellent machining properties.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Jahangir.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Jahangir (1605&amp;ndash;1627)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Akbar was&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;succeeded by Salim,&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;who ascended the throne in&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;October 1605 under the name of Jahangir.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Jahangir is remembered for the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;chain of justice&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Jahangir&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;hanged Arjundev, the 5th Guru of the Sikhs&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;for helping his&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;rebellious&amp;nbsp;son Khusaro.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Pleased with the success against&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Malik Ambar&lt;/span&gt;, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;vizier of Ahmed Nagar,&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;Jahangir conferred the title of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Shah Jahan on Khurram,&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;who later became&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Jahangir&amp;#39;s successor.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Jahangir established an&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Art gallery under the leadership of Aga Raza.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Jahangir&amp;#39;s time is called the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;golden age of painting.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Jahangir&amp;#39;s tomb&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;was&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;built by Nur Jahan.&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;​&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;:(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Humayun (1530&amp;ndash;1556)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Nasiruddin Humayun&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;ascended the throne on&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;29 December 1530.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Before ascending the throne, Humayun was the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;governor of Badakhshan.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In 1533, Humayun&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;established a new city&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;called&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Dinpanah.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The battle of&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Chausa took place between Sher Shah and Humayun&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;on June 25,&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;1539,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;In this war,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Sher Shah won.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Battle of&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Bilgram or Kannauj&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;took place in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;1540,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;in which&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Humayun was defeated, and Sher Shah captured Delhi.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;1555 (Battle of Sirhind)&lt;/span&gt;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Humayun defeated Sikandar&lt;/span&gt;, the Shuri ruler of Punjab, and&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;sat on the throne again.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Humayun&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;died in 1556&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;by falling down the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;stairs of the library&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;located in the Din Panah Bhawan.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Shah Jahan (1627&amp;ndash;1657)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Shah Jahan&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;ascended the throne in 1628.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In memory of his wife&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Mumtaz Mahal (Arjumand Bano Begum),&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;Shah Jahan built the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Taj Mahal on her tomb in Agra.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Ustad Isha designed&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;the Taj Mahal&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;chief&amp;nbsp;architect&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;who built the Taj Mahal was&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Ustad Ahmad Lahori.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Aurangzeb (1658&amp;ndash;1707)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Aurangzeb captured&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Agra and hastily&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;got his&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;coronation done on 31 July 1658&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;with the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;title of Alamgir.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;After being successful in the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;battle of Devrai&lt;/span&gt;, he got his&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;coronation done again on 5 June 1659,&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;thus Aurangzeb was the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;first and last Mughal emperor to be coronated twice.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Aurangzeb&amp;#39;s&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;teacher was Mir Muhammad Hakim.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Aurangzeb followed the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Sunni religion&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and was&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;called Zinda Pir.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Aurangzeb&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;reintroduced&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;1679 Jizya tax&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Aurangzeb built&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Bibi Ka Maqbara in Aurangabad (Maharashtra) in 1679.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

